title:
Wilf's question in numerical semigroups $S_3$ revisited and inequalities
  for rescaled genera

sections.text:
#### Abstract

We consider numerical semigroups $S_{3}=\left\langle d_{1}, d_{2}, d_{3}\right\rangle$, minimally generated by three positive integers. We revisit the Wilf question in $S_{3}$ and, making use of identities for degrees of syzygies of such semigroups, give a short proof of existence of an affirmative answer. We find the upper and lower bounds for rescaled genera of numerical semigroups $S_{3}$.


Key words: numerical semigroups, identities for degrees of syzygies, Wilf's question, 2000 Math. Subject Classification: Primary - 20M14, Secondary - 11P81.

## 1 INTRODUCTION

Let a numerical semigroup $S_{3}$ be minimally generated by a set of natural numbers $\left\{d_{1}, d_{2}, d_{3}\right\}$, where

$$
\operatorname{gcd}\left(d_{1}, d_{2}, d_{3}\right)=1, \quad 3 \leq d_{1}<d_{2}<d_{3} \leq d_{1} d_{2}-d_{1}-d_{2}
$$

and neither of its generators is linearly representable by the rest of them. Its generating function $H\left(S_{3} ; t\right)$

$$
H\left(S_{3} ; t\right)=\sum_{s \in S_{3}} t^{s}, \quad t<1, \quad 0 \in S_{3}
$$

is referred to as the Hilbert series of $S_{3}$ and has a rational representation (Rep),

$$
H\left(S_{3} ; t\right)=\frac{1-t^{x_{1}}-t^{x_{2}}-t^{x_{3}}+t^{y_{1}}+t^{y_{2}}}{\left(1-t^{d_{1}}\right)\left(1-t^{d_{2}}\right)\left(1-t^{d_{3}}\right)}, \quad x_{j}, y_{j} \in \mathbb{Z}_{}>
$$

where $x_{j}, y_{j}$ denote degrees of syzygies. The Frobenius number $F_{3}$ as a largest unrepresentable integer by the triple $\left\{d_{1}, d_{2}, d_{3}\right\}$, is often used in commutative algebra when shifting by unity, $c_{3}=F_{3}+1$, and referred to as a conductor of $S_{3}$. The largest degree $g_{3}=\max \left\{y_{1}, y_{2}\right\}$ is related to $F_{3}$,

$$
g_{3}=F_{3}+\sigma_{1}, \quad \sigma_{1}=d_{1}+d_{2}+d_{3}, \quad G_{0}=\# \Delta_{3}, \quad \Delta_{3}=\mathbb{Z}_{>} \backslash S_{3}
$$

where $\Delta_{3}$ and $G_{0}$ stand for the set of unrepresentable inetgers (gaps) and the genus of semigroup $S_{3}$. The set $\Delta_{3}$ comprises two sorts of gaps: those $s \in \Delta_{3}$ such that $F_{3}-s \notin \Delta_{3}$, and those $s \in \Delta_{3}$ such that $F_{3}-s \in \Delta_{3}$. Such dichotomy of the set $\Delta_{3}$ leads to a simple inequality

$$
w_{3} \geq \frac{1}{2}, \quad w_{3}=\frac{G_{0}}{c_{3}}
$$

and equality in (1.5) is arisen only for symmetric semigroups where $\Delta_{3}$ comprises only the 1st sort gaps. In fact, inequality (1.5) holds for numerical semigroups $S_{m}$ of any $m$, i.e., $w_{m} \geq 1 / 2$ where $w_{m}=G_{0} / c_{m}$. In 1978, Wilf [9] raised two questions (WQ) and the 1st of them was: is it true that for given $S_{m}$ holds

$$
w_{m} \leq \frac{m-1}{m}
$$

with equality only for the generators $m, m+1, \ldots, 2 m-1$ ? In a seminal paper [6], by means of embedding procedure for a sequence of partial gapsets of semigroup $S_{m}$, it was shown

$$
w_{m} \leq \frac{\tau_{m}}{\tau_{m}+1}
$$

where $\tau_{m}$ stands for the type of $S_{m}$. Inequality (1.7) coincides with (1.6) if $m=2,3$, but does not imply (1.6) if $m>3$. During the last decade, a vast literature [2] was devoted to Wilf's question which, despite the attention it attracted in various special cases, remains unsolved completely for non-symmetric semigroups $S_{m}, m \geq 4$.

Based on polynomial identities for degrees of syzygies [4], in the present paper, we suggest quite different approach to get an affirmative answer to WQ in semigroups $S_{3}$. In its framework we obtain also the lower bound for $F_{3}$ as well as the lower and upper bounds for rescaled genera of $S_{3}$. From the standpoint of WQ perspectives, the developed approach may be applied to semigroups $S_{m}, m \geq 4$. We plan to address this question in a separate paper.

# 2 SYZYGY IDENTITIES FOR NUMERICAL SEMIGROUPS $S_{3}$ 

Consider a numerical semigroup $S_{3}$ and write the polynomial identities (see [4], Theorem 1) for degrees of syzygies $x_{j}, y_{j}$. Denote by $X_{r}$ and $Y_{r}$ two power sums,

$$
\text { a) } \quad X_{r}=x_{1}^{r}+x_{2}^{r}+x_{3}^{r}, \quad \text { b) } \quad Y_{r}=y^{r}+g_{3}^{r}, \quad 0 \leq x_{j}, y<g_{3}
$$

and consider a set of polynomial equations for five real variables $x_{1}, x_{2}, x_{3}, y$ and $g_{3}$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \text { a) } \quad Y_{1}-X_{1}=0 \\
& \text { b) } \quad Y_{2}-X_{2}=2 \pi_{3}, \quad \pi_{3}=d_{1} d_{2} d_{3} \\
& \text { c) } \quad Y_{r+3}-X_{r+3}=\frac{(r+3)!}{r!} K_{r} \pi_{3}, \quad r \geq 0, \quad K_{r}>0
\end{aligned}
$$

where coefficients $K_{r}$ exhibit a linear combination of higher genera $G_{0}, \ldots, G_{r}$ of numerical semigroup $S_{3}$, i.e., $G_{r}=\sum_{s \in \Delta_{3}} s^{r}, r \geq 0$ (see formulas (22,23) in [5]).

E.g.,

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
K_{0}=G_{0}+\delta_{1}, & \delta_{k}=\frac{\sigma_{k}-1}{2^{k}} \\
K_{1}=G_{1}+\frac{\sigma_{1}}{2} G_{0}+\frac{3 \delta_{1}^{2}+\delta_{2}}{6}, & \sigma_{k}=d_{1}^{k}+d_{2}^{k}+d_{3}^{k} \\
K_{2}=G_{2}+\sigma_{1} G_{1}+\frac{3 \sigma_{1}^{2}+\sigma_{2}}{12} G_{0}+\frac{\delta_{1}\left(\delta_{1}^{2}+\delta_{2}\right)}{3}, & \text { etc. }
\end{array}
$$

Explicit expressions of $K_{r}$ are given in [5], formula (27).

# 2.1 LOWER BOUND OF $g_{3}$ 

Make use of Newton-Maclaurin's inequalities [10] for power sums $X_{j}$ and $Y_{j}$,

$$
\text { a) } \begin{aligned}
3 X_{2}>X_{1}^{2}, & \text { b) } \quad 2 Y_{2}>Y_{1}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

and substitute equality (2.2b) into inequality (2.4a)

$$
3\left(Y_{2}-2 \pi_{3}\right)>Y_{1}^{2}
$$

By (2.1b), find a relationship between $Y_{1}$ and $Y_{2}$,

$$
Y_{2}=Y_{1}^{2}-2 g_{3} Y_{1}+2 g_{3}^{2}
$$

and substitute it into (2.5),

$$
Y_{1}^{2}-3 g_{3} Y_{1}+3 g_{3}^{2}>3 \pi_{3}, \quad g_{3}<Y_{1}<2 g_{3}
$$

Denote by $u$ a ratio $Y_{1} / g_{3}$ and rescale (2.7) by $g_{3}$ as follows,

$$
\frac{g_{3}^{2}}{3 \pi_{3}}>P(u), \quad P(u)=\frac{1}{u^{2}-3 u+3}, \quad u=\frac{Y_{1}}{g_{3}}, \quad 1<u<2
$$

Find a range of $g_{3}$ where inequality (2.8) is satisfied for any $u \in(1,2)$. Since a convex function $P(u)$ reached its minimum $P(u)=1$ at $u=1,2$, we arrive at Davison's lower bound [1] for $g_{3}$,

$$
g_{3}>\sqrt{3 \pi_{3}}
$$

In fact, more accurate reasoning [3], e.g., $Y_{1} \leq 2 g_{3}-1$, leads to a slightly stronger bound, $\sqrt{3} \sqrt{\pi_{3}+1}$.

### 2.2 LOWER AND UPPER BOUNDS OF $h_{0}=K_{0} / g_{3}$

Introduce elementary symmetric polynomials

$$
\mathcal{X}_{1}=x_{1}+x_{2}+x_{3}, \quad \mathcal{X}_{2}=x_{1} x_{2}+x_{2} x_{3}+x_{3} x_{1}, \quad \mathcal{X}_{3}=x_{1} x_{2} x_{3}
$$

which are related by Newton's recursion identities to power sums $X_{k}$, defined in (2.1a),

$$
\mathcal{X}_{1}=X_{1}, \quad 2 \mathcal{X}_{2}=X_{1}^{2}-X_{2}, \quad 6 \mathcal{X}_{3}=X_{1}^{3}-3 X_{1} X_{2}+2 X_{3}
$$

Recall the Newton-Maclaurin inequalities [10] for polynomials $\mathcal{X}_{k}$,

$$
\text { a) } \frac{\mathcal{X}_{1}}{3} \geq\left(\frac{\mathcal{X}_{2}}{3}\right)^{1 / 2} \geq \mathcal{X}_{3}^{1 / 3}, \quad \text { b) } \quad\left(\frac{\mathcal{X}_{2}}{3}\right)^{2} \geq \frac{\mathcal{X}_{1}}{3} \mathcal{X}_{3}
$$

Consider the 2nd inequality in (2.12a), and substitute there identiies (2.11)

$$
\left(X_{1}^{2}-X_{2}\right)^{3} \geq 6\left(X_{1}^{3}-3 X_{1} X_{2}+2 X_{3}\right)^{2}
$$

Now, substitute into the last inequality three first equalities (2.2 a,b,c),

$$
\left(Y_{1}^{2}-Y_{2}+2 \pi_{3}\right)^{3} \geq 6\left(Y_{1}^{3}-3 Y_{1} Y_{2}+6 Y_{1} \pi_{3}+2 Y_{3}-12 \pi_{3} K_{0}\right)^{2}
$$

Combining identity for power sums, $2 Y_{3}=3 Y_{1} Y_{2}-Y_{1}^{3}$, and relation (2.6), we simplify (2.13)

$$
\left(g_{3} Y_{1}-g_{3}^{2}+\pi_{3}\right)^{3} \geq 27 \pi_{3}^{2}\left(2 K_{0}-Y_{1}\right)^{2}
$$

Introduce two new variables $v$ and $h_{0}$,

$$
v=\frac{\pi_{3}}{g_{3}^{2}}, \quad 0<v<\frac{1}{3}, \quad h_{0}=\frac{K_{0}}{g_{3}}, \quad \frac{1}{2} \leq h_{0} \leq w_{3}
$$

and rescale (2.14) by $g_{3}$

$$
\left(u-2 h_{0}\right)^{2} \leq Q(u, v), \quad Q(u, v)=\frac{(u-1+v)^{3}}{27 v^{2}}<Q(2, v)
$$

In (2.15), $v$ is bounded from above due to (2.9) and $h_{0}$ is bounded from below due to (1.5).
Find the upper bound of $h_{0}$ and represent (2.16) as follows,

$$
u<2 h_{0}+\sqrt{Q(2, v)}
$$

On the other hand, there holds always another inequality, $u<2$. In order to find the maximal value of $h_{0}$ when both inequalities still hold, we have to choose such $v$, which provides minimal value of $Q(2, v)$ at the interval $v \in(0,1 / 3)$, that happens at $v=1 / 3$. Thus, we arrive at equality

$$
2 h_{0}<2-\sqrt{Q(2,1 / 3)}=\frac{10}{9}
$$

and finally (see Figure 1),

$$
\frac{1}{2} \leq h_{0}<\frac{5}{9} \simeq 0.5555
$$

![img-0.jpeg](img-0.jpeg)

Figure 1: Plot of the function $\Phi(u, v)=\frac{1}{2}(u-\sqrt{Q(u, v)})$ and the points $\left(u, v, h_{0}\right)$ for semigroups $\langle 3,4,5\rangle$ (yellow), $\langle 4,5,6\rangle$ (purple), $\langle 5,6,7\rangle$ (blue), $\langle 11,17,29\rangle$ (red), $\langle 25,31,43\rangle$ (magenta), $\langle 23,29,44\rangle$ (cyan), $\langle 43,47,113\rangle$ (green), $\langle 501,503,603\rangle$ (black), $\langle 901,903,1003\rangle$ (gray) and $\langle 1201,1203,1303\rangle$ (orange).

# 2.3 WILF'S QUESTION IN $S_{3}$. 

Prove that WQ has an affirmative answer for all non-symmetric semigroups $S_{3}$ and start with $\left\langle 3, d_{2}, d_{3}\right\rangle$. Making use of Lemma 6 in [8], which established inequalities for such semigroups, we get:

$$
\frac{3 c_{3}}{2} \leq 3 G_{0}<2 c_{3}+1
$$

Replacing the r.h.s. of strict inequality on non-strict one, $3 G_{0} \leq 2 c_{3}$, we arrive at $w_{3} \leq 2 / 3$.
Consider numerical semigroups $S_{3}$ with $d_{1} \geq 4$ and, using relation $g_{3}=c_{3}+2 \delta_{1}$, and definition (2.15) of $h_{0}$ and expression (2.3) for $K_{0}$, represent inequality (2.19) for the upper bound as follows,

$$
w_{3}<\frac{5}{9}+\frac{e_{3}}{9}, \quad e_{3}=\frac{\delta_{1}}{c_{3}}
$$

A sufficient (not necessary) condition for affirmative answer to WQ would be inequality $e_{3} \leq 1$.

Theorem 1 Let a non-symmetric numerical semigroup $\left\langle d_{1}, d_{2}, d_{3}\right\rangle, d_{1} \geq 4$, be given and its generators satisfy (1.1). The WQ has an affirmative answer for all numerical semigroups $S_{3}$

Proof Instead of $e_{3}$, consider its inverse $1 / e_{3}$ and apply inequality (2.9),

$$
\frac{1}{e_{3}}=\frac{g_{3}}{\delta_{1}}-2>2\left(\frac{\sqrt{3 \pi_{3}}}{\sigma_{1}-1}-1\right)>2\left(\frac{\sqrt{3 \pi_{3}}}{\sigma_{1}}-1\right)
$$

According to (2.21), a sufficient (not necessary) condition to provide $e_{3}<1$ is the Diophantine inequality

$$
\rho_{3}<\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}} \simeq 1.1547, \quad d_{1} \geq 4, \quad \rho_{3}=\frac{d_{1}+d_{2}+d_{3}}{\sqrt{d_{1} d_{2} d_{3}}}
$$

Check its solvability for different triples $\left\{d_{1}, d_{2}, d_{3}\right\}$. For that purpose, represent (2.22) as follows

$$
\left(\sqrt{d_{3}}-\sqrt{d_{2}}\right)^{2}<2\left(\sqrt{\frac{d_{1}}{3}}-1\right) \sqrt{d_{2} d_{3}}-d_{1}
$$

that necessary leads to the lower bound of the product $d_{2} d_{3}$,

$$
d_{2} d_{3}>C\left(d_{1}\right), \quad C\left(d_{1}\right)=\frac{3}{4}\left(\frac{d_{1}}{\sqrt{d_{1}}-\sqrt{3}}\right)^{2}
$$

where the concave function $C\left(d_{1}\right)$ arrives its minimum $C(12)=36$ (see Figure 2).
![img-1.jpeg](img-1.jpeg)

Figure 2: Plot of functions $C\left(d_{1}\right)$ (in magenta) and $\left(d_{1}+1\right)\left(d_{1}+2\right)$ (in black). Blue dots correspond to semigroups with $\rho_{3}<1.1547, e_{3}<1$. Ten small and three large red dots correspond to semigroups with $\rho_{3}>1.1547, e_{3}<1$ and $\rho_{3}>1.1547, e_{3}>1$, respectively. These semigroups are listed in Table 1.

The criterion (2.24) has to be supplemented by another restriction, $d_{3}>d_{2}>d_{1}$, or

$$
d_{2} d_{3} \geq\left(d_{1}+1\right)\left(d_{1}+2\right)
$$

The first values of descendent sequence $\mathrm{C}(\mathrm{d} 1)$ are given below,

$$
C(4)=167.14, \quad C(5)=73.81, \quad C(6)=52.46, \quad C(7)=44.02, \quad \ldots
$$

The final criterion for generators $d_{j}$ to satisfy (2.24) reads,

$$
\text { 1) } \begin{aligned}
d_{1}=4, & d_{2} d_{3}>167, \quad 2) \quad d_{1}=5, \quad d_{2} d_{3}>73 \quad \text { 3) } \quad d_{1} \geq 6 .
\end{aligned}
$$

A brief analysis of (2.26) and restriction $d_{3}<d_{1} d_{2}-d_{1}-d_{2}$ give a short list of non-symmetric semigroups $S_{3}$ with $d_{1}=4,5$, where inequality (2.22) might be broken. Below we present Table 1 of 13 semigroups $S_{3}$, where $\rho_{3}>1.1547$.

Table 1

![table_0](table_0)

Ten semigroups $S_{3}$ among 13 in Table 1,
$\langle 4,7,9\rangle,\langle 4,7,17\rangle,\langle 4,9,11\rangle,\langle 4,9,15\rangle,\langle 4,11,13\rangle,\langle 5,6,7\rangle,\langle 5,6,8\rangle,\langle 5,7,8\rangle,\langle 5,7,9\rangle,\langle 5,8,9\rangle$,
have $\rho_{3}>1.1547$ and $e_{3}<1$, and, according to inequality (2.20), provide $w_{3}<2 / 3$. The rest three semigroups $S_{3}$,

$$
\langle 4,5,7\rangle, \quad\langle 4,5,11\rangle, \quad\langle 4,7,13\rangle
$$

have $\rho_{3}>1.1547$ and $e_{3}>1$, but a direct calculation gives

$$
w_{3}(\langle 4,5,7\rangle)=0.5714, \quad w_{3}(\langle 4,5,11\rangle)=0.625, \quad w_{3}(\langle 4,7,13\rangle)=0.6363
$$

Thus, Theorem is proven.
2.4 LOWER AND UPPER BOUNDS OF $h_{r}=K_{r} / g_{3}^{r+1}, r \geq 1$.

Consider four syzygy identities (2.2),

$$
Y_{1}-X_{1}=0, \quad Y_{2}-X_{2}=2 \pi_{3}, \quad Y_{3}-X_{3}=6 \pi_{3} K_{0}, \quad Y_{4}-X_{4}=24 \pi_{3} K_{1}
$$

Substituting into the fourth of them polynomial relations $Y_{4}\left(Y_{1}, Y_{2}\right)$ and $X_{4}\left(X_{1}, X_{2}, X_{3}\right.$ (see [5], formulas (37)),

$$
2 Y_{4}=Y_{2}^{2}+2 Y_{1}^{2} Y_{2}-Y_{1}^{4}, \quad 6 X_{4}=X_{1}^{4}-6 X_{1}^{2} X_{2}+8 X_{1} X_{3}+3 X_{2}^{2}
$$

we obtain

$$
3\left(Y_{2}^{2}+2 Y_{1}^{2} Y_{2}-Y_{1}^{4}\right)=X_{1}^{4}-6 X_{1}^{2} X_{2}+8 X_{1} X_{3}+3 X_{2}^{2}+144 \pi_{3} K_{1}
$$

Continuing to substitute into (2.28) three first identities (2.27) and one more $2 Y_{3}=3 Y_{1} Y_{2}-Y_{1}^{3}$,

$$
Y_{2}=Y_{1}^{2}-4 K_{0} Y_{1}+12 K_{1}+\pi_{3}
$$

and combining it with identity (2.6), we arrive at equality in rescaled variables $h_{1}, h_{0}, u, v$,

$$
12 h_{1}=2 u\left(2 h_{0}-1\right)+2-v, \quad h_{1}=\frac{K_{1}}{g_{3}^{2}}
$$

Making use of bounds $(2.8,2.14,2.19)$ for $u, v, h_{0}$, we arrive at lower and upper bounds for $h_{1}$,

$$
0.13889 \simeq \frac{5}{36}<h_{1}<\frac{11}{54} \simeq 0.20370
$$

Next, supplement (2.27) with one more identity from (2.2),

$$
Y_{5}-X_{5}=60 \pi_{3} K_{2}
$$

and substitute there polynomial relations $Y_{5}\left(Y_{1}, Y_{2}\right)$ and $X_{5}\left(X_{1}, X_{2}, X_{3}\right)$ (see [5], formulas (37)), and the other three first identities (2.2). Skipping lengthy calculations, we present the final equality (see [5], formulas (39)),

$$
Y_{1}^{3}-2 K_{0} Y_{1}^{2}+4 \pi_{3} K_{0}+24 K_{2}=Y_{2}\left(Y_{1}+2 K_{0}\right)
$$

and combine it with identity (2.6). We present the final formula in rescaled variables $h_{2}, h_{0}, u, v$,

$$
12 h_{2}=\left(2 h_{0}-1\right) u(u-1)+2 h_{0}(1-v), \quad h_{2}=\frac{K_{2}}{g_{3}^{3}}
$$

Making use of bounds $(2.8,2.14,2.19)$ for $u, v, h_{0}$, we arrive at lower and upper bounds for $h_{2}$,

$$
0.05555 \simeq \frac{1}{18}<h_{2}<\frac{1}{9} \simeq 0.11111
$$

The ratios $h_{r}=K_{r} / g_{3}^{r+1}, r \geq 0$, will be referred to as rescaled genera of numerical semigroup $S_{3}$.
To study the bounds of $h_{r}, r \geq 3$, we make worth of Theorem 2 in [5], applied to semigroups $S_{3}$ : there exists an algebraic equation $R\left(h_{0}, h_{1}, h_{2}, h_{r}\right)=0$, where the polynomial $R\left(t_{1}, t_{2}, t_{3}, t_{4}\right)$ is irreducible over a ring $A\left[t_{1}, t_{2}, t_{3}, t_{4}\right]$. Avoiding lengthy formulas of $R\left(h_{0}, h_{1}, h_{2}, h_{r}\right)$ with growing $r$, we present one algebraic equation for $r=3$, making use of formula (42) in [5],

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(10 h_{3}-18 h_{1}^{2}+v h_{0}^{2}-\frac{v^{2}}{24}\right) \Delta_{1}=\Delta_{2}^{2} \\
& \Delta_{1}=3 h_{1}-2 h_{0}^{2}+\frac{v}{4}, \quad \Delta_{2}=6 h_{2}-6 h_{0} h_{1}+\frac{v}{2} h_{0}
\end{aligned}
$$

Substituting $(2.29,2.32)$ into (2.34), we obtain

$$
\Delta_{1}=\frac{1}{2}\left(2 h_{0}-1\right)\left(u-1-2 h_{0}\right), \quad \Delta_{2}=u \Delta_{1}
$$

that substantially simplifies equality (2.34),

$$
10 h_{3}=18 h_{1}^{2}-v h_{0}^{2}+\frac{v^{2}}{24}+u^{2} \Delta_{1}
$$

Making use of bounds $(2.8,2.14,2.19,2.30)$, we arrive at lower and upper bounds for $h_{3}$,

$$
0.02443<h_{3}<0.07515
$$

# 2.5 RESCALED GENERA $h_{r}$ IN SYMMETRIC SEMIGROUPS $S_{3}$ 

Every symmetric semigroup $S_{3}$ is a complete intersection [7] and therefore we can apply formulas (67) in [5] to calculate the six first rescaled genera $h_{r}, 1 \leq r \leq 6$, and find their lower and upper bounds. Bearing in mind that

$$
h_{0}=\frac{1}{2}, \quad u=1, \quad 0<v \leq \frac{1}{4}
$$

we get

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
h_{1}=\frac{1}{6}\left(1-\frac{1}{2} v\right), & 0.14583 \simeq \frac{7}{48}<h_{1}<\frac{1}{6} \simeq 0.16666 \\
h_{2}=\frac{1}{12}(1-v), & 0.06250 \simeq \frac{1}{16}<h_{2}<\frac{1}{12} \simeq 0.08333 \\
h_{3}=\frac{1}{20}\left(1-\frac{3}{2} v+\frac{1}{3} v^{2}\right), & 0.03229 \simeq \frac{31}{960}<h_{3}<\frac{1}{20} \simeq 0.05 \\
h_{4}=\frac{1}{30}\left(1-2 v+v^{2}\right), & 0.01875 \simeq \frac{3}{160}<h_{4}<\frac{1}{30} \simeq 0.03333 \\
h_{5}=\frac{1}{42}\left(1-\frac{5}{2} v+2 v^{2}-\frac{1}{4} v^{3}\right), & 0.01181 \simeq \frac{127}{10752}<h_{5}<\frac{1}{42} \simeq 0.02381 \\
h_{6}=\frac{1}{56}\left(1-3 v+\frac{10}{3} v^{2}-v^{3}\right), & 0.00791 \simeq \frac{85}{10752}<h_{6}<\frac{1}{56} \simeq 0.01785
\end{array}
$$

Making use of (2.19) and comparing the upper and lower bounds in $(2.30,2.33,2.36)$ with those in (2.37), we conclude that the domain of variation of $h_{r}, 0 \leq r \leq 3$, in non-symmetric semigroups $S_{3}$ contains their upper and lower bounds in symmetric semigroups $S_{3}$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
0.5=0.5 & =h_{0}=0.5<0.55555 \\
0.13889<0.14593 & <h_{1}<0.16666<0.20370 \\
0.05555<0.06250 & <h_{2}<0.08333<0.11111 \\
0.02443<0.03229 & <h_{3}<0.05000<0.07515
\end{aligned}
$$

e.g., $h_{1}(\langle 4,7,13\rangle)=0.169406, h_{1}(\langle 5,8,9\rangle)=0.169694$.

We leave open a question of whether such a property for the other rescaled genera $h_{r}$ with arbitrary $r \geq 4$ exists in numerical semigroups $S_{3}$.

abstract:
We consider numerical semigroups $S_3 = \langle d_1,d_2,d_3\rangle$,
minimally generated by three positive integers. We revisit the Wilf question in
